198. J Int Med Res. 1992 Jun;20(3):279-88. doi: 10.1177/030006059202000310.

Results of long-term follow-up after compensated fixed-dose therapy for 
thyrotoxicosis.

Zaini A(1), Khir A, Doi SA, Chan SP, Paramsothy M, Khoo BH.

Author information:
(1)Department of Medicine, University Hospital, University of Malaya, Kuala 
Lumpar.

To evaluate the effects of simple compensated fixed-dose iodine-131 therapy for 
thyrotoxicosis, the long-term results for 74 patients treated with a fixed dose 
of iodine-131 ranging from 5 to 12 mCi (185 to 444 MBq) were evaluated in the 
first 2 years of a trial. The dose selected was loosely based on the gross size 
of the thyroid gland. Routine antithyroid drug therapy was given for a minimum 
of 3 months after iodine-131 therapy. The mean (+/- SD) duration of follow-up 
was 74.5 +/- 42 months. The results indicated that roughly 25% of patients 
treated in this way will become hypothyroid after 5 years and that 85% are cured 
(need no further therapy during the follow-up period) using a single dose of 
iodine-131. Of those cured using a single iodine-131 dose, 81% were no longer 
receiving drugs after 6 months and 85% after 1 year. Such a regimen seems 
currently to be among the best available where prolonged periods of 
medication-free euthyroidism after therapy are sought.

